{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524086"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:01:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:01:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13974"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13974"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.08,0.05,0.71,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6608"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111079"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6608","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6608"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13974"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93200"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2636"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13369"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31257"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31258"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45150"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111079"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of generalised colicky abdominal pain which has now shifted to the right iliac fossa and become constant. She feels nauseated but has not vomited. She does not have any other symptoms. Her medical history is unremarkable and she does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly unwell. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 116/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft, with minimal tenderness in the right iliac fossa. There is no guarding or rebound tenderness. Bowel sounds are normal. A CT scan of the abdomen is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carcinoma of the caecum","Psoas abscess","Right ureteric calculus","Mucocele of the appendix","Right femoral hernia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a cystic mass in the right iliac fossa, contiguous with the faecally-loaded caecum, consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Emucocele of the appendix\u003C/strong\u003E (Image). There are areas of calcification within the wall of the appendix, suggesting a chronic process. Mucoceles of the appendix are uncommon but important to recognise due to their malignant potential. These neoplasms can metastasise and spread locally, potentially leading to pseudomyxoma peritonei. To minimise the risk of spillage and peritoneal seeding, these tumours are best managed by right hemicolectomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the caecum\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a solid mass rather than a cystic lesion. While it can cause similar symptoms of right lower quadrant pain and changes in bowel habits, the imaging findings would be different. Caecal carcinomas usually appear as irregular wall thickening or a solid mass arising from the caecal wall, often with associated lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epsoas abscess\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as a fluid collection within or adjacent to the psoas muscle. It would not be contiguous with the caecum and would not show calcifications in its wall. Patients with psoas abscesses often have more systemic symptoms such as fever, and may have a history of back pain or difficulty extending the hip.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eright ureteric calculus\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as a high-density (radio-opaque) lesion within the ureter. It would not present as a cystic mass and would not be connected to the caecum. Patients with ureteric calculi typically have severe, colicky flank pain radiating to the groin, often associated with haematuria and urinary symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eright femoral hernia\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as a protrusion through the femoral canal, below the inguinal ligament. It would not be located within the abdominal cavity or connected to the caecum. Femoral hernias typically present as a painful lump in the upper thigh, just below the groin crease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the patient underwent a right hemicolectomy, and the pathology confirmed a mucinous cystadenoma of the appendix. This highlights the importance of recognising this condition and managing it appropriately to prevent potential complications such as pseudomyxoma peritonei.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mucocele of the appendix presents as a cystic mass in the right iliac fossa on CT imaging, often with calcifications in the wall.","Mucoceles of the appendix have malignant potential and can lead to pseudomyxoma peritonei if ruptured.","Right hemicolectomy is the preferred treatment for mucocele of the appendix to minimize the risk of rupture and peritoneal seeding."],"references":["Rymer B, Forsythe RO, Husada G. Mucocoele and mucinous tumours of the appendix: A review of the literature. Int J Surg. 2015; 18:132-35."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93200"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13974"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20867"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22017"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"